St. James Parish Government has implemented a new central call center to field resident service requests, complaints, and needs. One of the primary goals of this initiative is to improve efficiency and transparency as it relates to our resident‚Äôs requests for parish services.

A three-person Citizens Service Center will be housed within the Operations Department at the parish government complex. It will be equipped with online services to better track citizen service requests, whether through the telephone or via online.

The hours of operation for the call center are 7:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. Monday through Thursday, and 7:30 a.m. to 11:30 a.m. on Fridays. Residents can call 225-562-2500 to speak directly to a call center operator that will either provide parish information, transfer a call to the appropriate department, or place a work order for requested services.

Residents will also be able to track or place a request for services online 24 hours a day at https://arcg.is/1jmnbj.

August 24 at 12:12 PM ¬∑

7AM Monday: What can we expect from üåÄ Marco üåÄ today? Marco is significantly weaker this morning and is located off the coast of SE LA. We still have the potential for heavy rainfall and coastal flooding/storm surge. Some gusty winds are possible along the coastal areas.

Heavy Rainfall:üåß
There is still a threat of heavy rainfall today, particularly along the SE LA coast and MS coastal areas.
-3 to 5 inches with locally higher amounts of rainfall is possible today.
-This is dependent upon where any bands associated with Marco set up today.

Storm Surge/Coastal Flooding:üåä
-There is the potential for 2 to 4 feet of storm surge/coastal flooding from Morgan City to Ocean Springs
-There is the potential for 2 to 3 feet in Lake Pontchartrain and Maurepas
-There is the potential for 2 to 3 feet from Ocean Springs to the AL state line.

Tornado Threat:üå™
-There is also still the threat for tornadoes today inside thunderstorms/banding from Marco.
-These tornadoes would be short-lived and fast moving.

A Hurricane Warning has been issued for St. James Parish.

Tropical Storm Marco is expected to bring tropical storm to hurricane conditions along with storm surge to southeast Louisiana and south Mississippi on Monday.

Tropical Storm Laura is forecast to enter the Gulf of Mexico by Monday night. Thereafter, Laura is likely to intensify into a hurricane while approaching the north-central to northwest Gulf coast region Wednesday and Wednesday night.

Please continue to monitor local weather stations and prepare your homes and your families for these storms.

shared_text:
NOAA NWS National Hurricane Center
August 20 at 6:12 PM ¬∑

The National Hurricane Center is issuing advisories on Tropical Depression Thirteen, located several hundred miles east of the northern Leeward Islands - www.nhc.noaa.gov/#Thirteen - and on newly formed Tropical Depression Fourteen, located a couple of hundred miles east of the Honduras/Nicaragua border www.nhc.noaa.gov/Fourteen.

Elsewhere over the Alantic basin on this Thursday afternoon, a tropical wave is nearing the western Africa coast, producing disorganized showers and thunderstorms within a few hundred miles of the coastline. This wave is expected to move over the far eastern tropical Atlantic on Friday, and some slow development is possible through the weekend while it moves west-northwestward at 15 to 20 mph across the eastern tropical Atlantic. It has a low (20 percent) chance of formation during the next 48 hours and a medium (40 percent) chance during the next five days. www.hurricanes.gov

Boil Advisory for Water System Customers in the Town of Gramercy (Including Residents Behind Sandwich World)

Tuesday, August 18, 2020 ‚Äì There has been a main line water break in Gramercy and the water system is issuing a Boil Water Advisory effective immediately for water customers in the Town of Gramercy, including residents behind Sandwich World. Please expect low water pressure during this time.

The water system will rescind this boil advisory upon notification from the Louisiana Department of Health ‚Äì Office of Public Health that additional water samples collected from our water supply system have shown our water to be safe.

For notification alerts regarding this matter or other emergency alerts, please visit https://member.everbridge.net/index/453003085618540#/login to register for St. James Parish Government Everbridge Alerts. Also, be a friendly neighbor and notify residents who may not have access to social media nor the alert system. For questions, please call the Town of Gramercy, (225) 869-4403.

shared_text:
NOAA NWS National Hurricane Center
August 12 at 2:51 PM ¬∑

...DEPRESSION REMAINS JUST BELOW TROPICAL STORM STRENGTH...

There are no coastal watches or warnings in effect.

At 11 a.m. AST, the center of Tropical Depression Eleven was located over the tropical Atlantic Ocean about 1320 miles (2125 km) east-southeast of the Lesser Antilles. It's moving toward the west near 14 mph (22 km/h), and this general motion is expected to continue today. A turn toward the west-northwest at a similar forward speed is expected tonight, with this motion continuing through the rest of the week.

Maximum sustained winds are near 35 mph (55 km/h) with higher gusts. Gradual strengthening is forecast to take place during the next 48 hours, and the depression is expected to become a tropical storm later today. When that occurs, it will be named Josephine.

The next complete advisory will be issued by NHC at 5 p.m. AST - www.hurricanes.gov

St. James Parish Government has implemented a new central call center to field resident service requests, complaints, and needs. One of the primary goals of this initiative is to improve efficiency and transparency as it relates to our resident‚Äôs requests for parish services.

A three-person Citizens Service Center will be housed within the Operations Department at the parish government complex. It will be equipped with online services to better track citizen service requests, whether through the telephone or via online.

The hours of operation for the call center are 7:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. Monday through Thursday, and 7:30 a.m. to 11:30 a.m. on Fridays. Residents can call 225-562-2500 to speak directly to a call center operator that will either provide parish information, transfer a call to the appropriate department, or place a work order for requested services.

Residents will also be able to track or place a request for services online 24 hours a day at https://arcg.is/1jmnbj.

Due to the potential for heavy rainfall throughout the weekend, Operations crews are taking the appropriate actions and flood control measures on both the east and west banks. The weir gates are closed and a water level of two feet will be maintained.

Please stay alert and tuned in to local weather stations for the latest advisories and follow all weather related safety instructions.
shared_text:
US National Weather Service New Orleans Louisiana
July 23 at 6:16 PM ¬∑

Showers and thunderstorms the next couple days will be capable of producing periods of heavy rainfall. Heavy rainfall can quickly lead to ponding of water on area roads - especially in low lying and poor drainage areas. It can also result in significantly reduced visibility. Follow the tips below to stay safe:

* Use extra caution when driving
* Be prepared for sudden changes in visibility
* Slow down to avoid hydroplaning
* Leave extra space between you and the car in front of you
* Never drive through a flooded road. The water may be too deep for safe passing
* Use your headlights, but do NOT drive with your hazards lights on

post_text:
St. James Parish Government has implemented a new central call center to field resident service requests, complaints, and needs. One of the primary goals of this initiative is to improve efficiency and transparency as it relates to our resident‚Äôs requests for parish services.

A three-person Citizens Service Center will be housed within the Operations Department at the parish government complex. It will be equipped with online services to better track citizen service requests, whether through the telephone or via online.

The hours of operation for the call center are 7:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. Monday through Thursday, and 7:30 a.m. to 11:30 a.m. on Fridays. Residents can call 225-562-2500 to speak directly to a call center operator that will either provide parish information, transfer a call to the appropriate department, or place a work order for requested services.

Residents will also be able to track or place a request for services online 24 hours a day at https://arcg.is/1jmnbj.

St. John the Baptist Parish
July 21 at 9:13 PM ¬∑

Governor Extends Phase Two Until August 7, 2020

Today, Tuesday, July 21, 2020 Governor John Bel Edwards announced that he is extending Phase Two of Reopening in Louisiana for an additional two weeks until August 7, 2020.

As a reminder, additional restrictions in Phase Two include:
-A mask mandate for ages eight and older unless the individual meets an exemption exception as outlined in the full order.
-All Bars with and without LDH food permits are closed indoors. Bars can offer curbside pickup.
-Indoor gatherings are limited to 50 people.

The Governor‚Äôs Office will post the updated proclamation later this week via gov.louisiana.gov. Businesses can send reopening questions to stjohnstrong@stjohn-la.gov or register at opensafely.gov.

St. James Parish Hospital is sharing a COVID-19 Update.
July 21 at 9:20 PM ¬∑

HOSPITAL UPDATE
St. James Parish Hospital and neighboring facilities are once again seeing more hospitalized COVID-19 patients that need specialized care to survive.

In our last update, only two weeks ago, about 25% of our inpatients were positive or presumed positive for COVID-19. Today, that number has grown to 60%.

We have taken precautions to keep all patients safe and separated, but we need our community to follow recommendations that help slow the spread.

Protect yourself, protect others and give us a better chance to have the capacity to care for our community.

Governor John Bel Edwards
July 20 at 1:18 PM ¬∑

Starting today, I am beginning three days of fasting and prayer for our state through July 22. The people of Louisiana need our prayers right now.

If you are inclined, please join me, First Lady Donna Edwards and faith leaders from across Louisiana in prayerful reflection and fasting on these three days. I encourage and welcome people of all faiths and denominations to participate.

I believe in the power of prayer and I believe in the power of working together and being good neighbors to overcome COVID-19. As the Bible says: Faith without works is dead. #lagov

HOSPITAL-WIDE VISITOR UPDATE
Effective 7.14.20, essential visitors allowed into the hospital, ER and clinics will include a parent/guardian of a minor patient, a caregiver of a patient who cannot consent for them self or a caregiver for someone needing end of life care. All essential visitors must be at least 18.

*Modifications to our visitor policy are based on the active COVID-19 cases per capita in St. James Parish as reported by the Louisiana Department of Health.

St. James Parish Government, Department of Human Resources, Community Action Agency has Community Services Block Grant funding available to provide online financial literacy sessions to St. James Parish 2020 High School Graduates and College Students. Participants will learn money management, credit, budgeting, and saving tips. Upon completion of the program, students will be issued a $250 stipend. To apply, the following documents are required:

Driver‚Äôs license or picture i.d. for head of household and/or student social security card
proof of household income
high school diploma and/or college i.d. from the current semester for students who are enrolled in college

Program registration will be held July 13, 2020 -July 17, 2020. To apply or for more information, call (225) 562-2447 or (225) 562-2313.

Governor John Bel Edwards
June 19 at 5:00 PM ¬∑

I have declared today, June 19, 2020, as Juneteenth Observance Day in Louisiana. On Juneteenth, we celebrate the end of slavery in America and we honor the history and contributions of African Americans in our country.

Juneteenth is a celebration of freedom and justice and it is a reminder of the strength and resolve of African Americans throughout history.

Honoring Juneteenth gives us all an opportunity to develop a greater and deeper understanding and appreciation of the experiences of African Americans. As we take time to reflect today, may we all recommit ourselves to the ongoing fight for equity and justice. #Juneteenth #lagov

post_text:
To All Residents of Molaison in South Vacherie:

St. James Utilities Department will be conducting smoke testing of the sanitary sewer system today beginning at 8:00 a.m. This study will involve the opening and entering of manholes in the streets and public utility easements. An important task of the testing will be to locate breaks and defects in the sewer system.

A special non-toxic smoke will be used in these tests. The smoke is manufactured for this purpose, leaves no residuals or stains, and has no effect on plant or animal life. The smoke has a distinctive, but not unpleasant, odor. Visibility and odor last only a few minutes, where there is adequate ventilation.

We ask if you know someone that lives in the community and does not have social media please pass this notice along. If you have any further questions, please contact the Utility Department at (225) 562-2551.

St. James Parish Operations crews are continuing the major drainage projects that were started prior to the COVID-19 pandemic. In preparation for hazardous weather, all crews are removing fallen trees from channels and clearing as much debris as possible.

Additionally, 18,000 sandbags are in stock, 500 yards of fill material has been delivered, and all is ready to deploy on both the east and west banks of the parish.

Inspections are being conducted on all fixed and mobile pumps and gates in the event that they would be used. Operations staff meetings have been conducted to prepare for road, bridge and waterway incidents, debris removal, flood control operations, and facility preparations.

Now is the time to make the necessary preparations at your home and for your family's needs. #GetAGamePlan

post_text:
St. James Parish Emergency Operations Department has been receiving updates regarding Tropical Storm Cristobal, which is expected to be a heavy rainfall event late this week into early next week. Although track and intensity are uncertain at this time, it is never too early to #GetAGamePlan.

As the parish continues to improve the drainage systems, there are still some areas that need work. Residents are asked to clean yards from fallen leaves and tree branches to avoid entering the drainage system ahead of this weather event. Also, please continue removing any debris from catch basins and storm drains that may impede drainage or become projectiles.

Now is a good time to pull out hurricane checklists and be sure your essential items are stocked. St. James Parish officials are monitoring weather conditions and will update as necessary.

June 2 at 4:52 PM ¬∑

A look from above, at what we're now calling Tropical Storm #Cristobal.

The system is forecast to begin moving northward across the Gulf of Mexico by this weekend. However, it is too soon to specify the location and timing of any potential impacts along the U.S. Gulf Coast. Interests in these areas should monitor the progress of this
system through the week and ensure they have their hurricane plan in place as we begin the season.

shared_text:
NOAA NWS National Hurricane Center
June 2 at 4:31 PM ¬∑

...DEPRESSION STRENGTHENS TO A TROPICAL STORM...

Observations from an Air Force Reserve Unit Hurricane Hunter aircraft indicate that Tropical Depression Three has strengthened into Tropical Storm Cristobal (pronounced krees-TOH-bahl). The maximum winds are estimated to be 40 mph (65 km/h) with higher gusts.

It's centered as of 11:15 a.m. CDT about 150 miles (245 km) west-southwest of Campeche, Mexico, moving toward the west-southwest at 3 mph (km/h).

The next complete advisory will be issued by NHC at 4 p.m. CDT with an intermediate advisory at 1 p.m. CDT www.hurricanes.gov

Governor John Bel Edwards
May 19 at 5:30 PM ¬∑

This time of year, we focus a lot of attention on the start of hurricane season--and for good reason. But flooding, tornadoes and other severe weather happen much more often and it‚Äôs important to always be ready for a variety of different scenarios that we are all too familiar with in Louisiana.

GetAGamePlan.org is a great resource for emergency preparedness tips and information, including the Louisiana Emergency Preparedness Guide. And of course, this time around you should include items like masks or facial coverings, hand sanitizer, and the like as we still have to continue fighting COVID-19 during hurricane season. #lagov

SCHEDULED WATER SHUT OFF:

To the residents of Cambre Street, Canal Street, Kinler Street, Lucky Street, Schexnayder Street, Laiche Street, South Nobile Street, Paul Gaudet Street, Gaudet Street, Brignac Street, Guidry Road, Morgan Street, and Matherne Road, on Tuesday, May 19, 2020 beginning at 8:00 a.m. the water will be shut off to repair the main water line. The St. James Parish Utilities Department will be making these repairs. Once water is restored, all residents will be under a BOIL WATER ADVISORY until the Utilities Department is notified by the state that the Boil Water Advisory is lifted.

Any questions, please contact the St. James Parish Utilities Office at 225-562-2551.
